snippet.textDisplay: A console, any console, IS just a computing device, and therefore a computer, therefore a PC. XBOX and PlayStation consoles have always been 'PCs'. But is is a console. It does not become more of a PC because its shape changed. It is the same thing on the inside as it always has been, with upgraded hardware. Calling it a PC suddenly because it is now more square seems silly to me. I happen to like the new shape, a lot. I don't call that new shape 'PC' suddenly - it is still classified as a console because it is meant for dedicated gaming and not for general personal computing. No, it is not a PC because it has a more boxlike shape than its predecessors.

snippet.textDisplay: I think I have more console loyalty to Xbox rather than PS.  I've owned a PS4 Pro but I gave that console to my brother.  I bought the first gen. I own a Windows PC with a GTX 1060 6gbvram, 8100 i3, 8gb ram, SATA ssd and I have Steam installed to play games on that PC.  I'm in my mid 40's so I grew up with a lot of game consoles over the years.   I like Nintendo (a lot).  I like Microsoft. Playstation has exclusives to wave under my nose for it's hardware, I already am a Microsoft customer on pc so they have me there.  I don't have to have a console to play everything they have to offer in the foreseeable future, that includes my library of media I've bought and will likely still buy from them. (hooking up a pc to a tv isn't hard so I'm not losing there)  I am not saying this is bad.  It's a very pro consumer move for Microsoft and they should get kudos for it but it will make me slower to run out and buy one unless it hits the impulse buy level in pricing.  Playstation only has exclusives to grab me with (I know important, but the actual numbers here that won't be on pc as well will not be large.  Just look at last gen.) but microsoft already has me for the next gen as far as their games.  It's just a different race than it was for xbox one and ps4.  We shall see.
